ined</strong><br> 19 Step-by-Step Examples!</h1>
<p class=3D"entry-date">// Last Updated: <time datetime=3D"2020-01-21">Janu=
ary 21, 2020</time> - <a href=3D"https://calcworkshop.com/triangle-trig/soh=
cahtoa/#chapter">Watch Video</a> //</p></header><div class=3D"entry-content=
"><p>In this geometry lesson, you=E2=80=99re going to learn all about SohCa=
hToa.</p>
<div id=3D"attachment_16379" style=3D"width: 610px" class=3D"wp-caption ali=
gnright"><img aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-16379" src=3D"https://=
calcworkshop.com/wp-content/uploads/jenn-calcworkshop-sohcahtoa.jpg" alt=3D=
"Jenn (B.S., M.Ed.) of Calcworkshop=C2=AE teaching soh-cah-toa" width=3D"60=
0" height=3D"338" data-pin-nopin=3D"true" class=3D"size-full wp-image-16379=
"><p id=3D"caption-attachment-16379" class=3D"wp-caption-text">Jenn, Founde=
r Calcworkshop<sup>=C2=AE</sup>, 15+ Years Experience (Licensed &amp; Certi=
fied Teacher)</p></div>
<p>It=E2=80=99s probably one of the most famous math mnemonics alongside PE=
MDAS.</p>
<p>And it=E2=80=99s an essential technique for your mathematical toolbelt.<=
/p>
<p><i>Let=E2=80=99s get to it!</i></p>
<h2>What Is SohCahToa?</h2>
<p>It=E2=80=99s a mnemonic device to help you remember the three basic <str=
ong>trig ratios</strong> used to solve for missing sides and angles in a ri=
ght triangle.  </p>
<p>It=E2=80=99s defined as:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SOH</strong>: Sin(=CE=B8) =3D Opposite / Hypotenuse</li>
<li><strong>CAH</strong>: Cos(=CE=B8) =3D Adjacent / Hypotenuse</li>
<li><strong>TOA</strong>: Tan(=CE=B8) =3D Opposite / Adjacent</li>
</ul>
<p>We=E2=80=99ll dive further into the theory behind it in the video below,=
 but essentially it=E2=80=99s taken from the <a href=3D"https://calcworksho=
p.com/similarity/aa-postulate/">AA Similarity Postulate</a> that we learned=
 about previously.  It stated that the ratios of the lengths of two sides o=
f similar right triangles are equal.  Therefore, the sets of ratios depend =
only on the measure of the acute angle, not the size of the triangle.</p>
<blockquote><p><b>Key Point</b>: Regardless of the size of the triangle, th=
ese trigonometric ratios will always hold true for right triangles.</p></bl=
ockquote>
<p>Remember the three basic ratios are called <strong>Sine</strong>, <stron=
g>Cosine</strong>, and <strong>Tangent</strong>, and they represent the fou=
ndational <strong>Trigonometric Ratios</strong>, after the Greek word for t=
riangle measurement.  </p>
<p>And these trigonometric ratios allow us to find missing sides of a right=
 triangle, as well as missing angles.</p>
<h2>How To Remember Trig Functions?</h2>
<p>So how do we remember these three trig ratios and use them to solve for =
missing sides and angles?</p>
<div class=3D"one-half first">
First, we remember how the sides of a right triangle are labeled:<p></p>
<ul>
<li>Opposite Leg</li>
<li>Adjacent Leg</li>
<li>Hypotenuse</li>
</ul>
<p>The opposite leg is opposite one of the acute angles, the adjacent leg i=
s next to the acute angle, and the hypotenuse is opposite the right angle, =
as it=E2=80=99s the longest side, as noted by the <a href=3D"http://jwilson=
.coe.uga.edu/EMAT6680/Adcock/Adcock6690/RLAInstructUnit1/RlaTrigLesson3.htm=
" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">University of Georgia</a>.
</p></div>
<div class=3D"one-half">
<div id=3D"attachment_16381" style=3D"width: 1290px" class=3D"wp-caption al=
igncenter"><img aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-16381" src=3D"https:=
//calcworkshop.com/wp-content/uploads/opposite-adjacent-hypotenuse-diagram.=
png" alt=3D"opposite adjacent hypotenuse diagram" width=3D"1280" height=3D"=
720" data-pin-nopin=3D"true" class=3D"size-full wp-image-16381"><p id=3D"ca=
ption-attachment-16381" class=3D"wp-caption-text">Right Triangle Diagram</p=
></div>
</div>
<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>
<p>Then we use the mnemonic device we talk about earlier: <strong>SOHCAHTOA=
!</strong></p>
<div id=3D"attachment_16382" style=3D"width: 1290px" class=3D"wp-caption al=
igncenter"><img aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-16382" src=3D"https:=
//calcworkshop.com/wp-content/uploads/sohcahtoa-chart.png" alt=3D"sohcahtoa=
 chart" width=3D"1280" height=3D"720" data-pin-nopin=3D"true" class=3D"size=
-full wp-image-16382"><p id=3D"caption-attachment-16382" class=3D"wp-captio=
n-text">SOH-CAH-TOA Chart</p></div>
<p>An easy way to remember the order of Sin, Cos, and Tan is to use saying =
such as:</p>
<p><em>Some Of Her Children Are Having Trouble Over Algebra</em></p>
<p>If you can remember the order of the trigonometric functions, then a qui=
cker saying would be:</p>
<p><em>Oscar Had A Heap Of Apples</em></p>
<p>Modifying our equations from earlier, we have:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SOH</strong>: Sin(=CE=B8) =3D Oscar / Had</li>
<li><strong>CAH</strong>: Cos(=CE=B8) =3D A / Heap</li>
<li><strong>TOA</strong>: Tan(=CE=B8) =3D Of / Apples</li>
</ul>
<p>There are many more <a href=3D"https://www.pleacher.com/mp/mfacts/mobsoh=
.html" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener" target=3D"=E2=80=9C_blank=E2=80=9D">fun =
sayings</a> as well.</p>
<h2>Few Examples=E2=80=A6</h2>
<p>Given the following right triangle, solve for the missing side length, r=
:<br>
</p><div id=3D"attachment_16395" style=3D"width: 1290px" class=3D"wp-captio=
n aligncenter"><img aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-16395" src=3D"ht=
tps://calcworkshop.com/wp-content/uploads/find-hypotenuse-using-sin.png" al=
t=3D"how to find hypotenuse with sin" width=3D"1280" height=3D"720" data-pi=
n-nopin=3D"true" class=3D"size-full wp-image-16395"><p id=3D"caption-attach=
ment-16395" class=3D"wp-caption-text">Using Sin to Find the Hypotenuse</p><=
/div><p></p>
<p>Sometimes we are given two sides lengths, and we need to determine one o=
f the acute angles of the right triangle.  </p>
<p><i>How can we do this?</i></p>
<p><strong>Inverse Trig Ratios</strong> allow us to solve for those missing=
 angles quite easily.  Consequently, SOHCAHTOA is very versatile as it gran=
ts us the ability to solve for sides and angles of a right triangle!</p>
<div id=3D"attachment_16376" style=3D"width: 1290px" class=3D"wp-caption al=
igncenter"><img aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-16376" src=3D"https:=
//calcworkshop.com/wp-content/uploads/inverse-trig-values.png" alt=3D"inver=
se trig values" width=3D"1280" height=3D"720" data-pin-nopin=3D"true" class=
=3D"size-full wp-image-16376"><p id=3D"caption-attachment-16376" class=3D"w=
p-caption-text">Inverse Trig Values</p></div>
<p>In the next example we are asked to =E2=80=9CSolve the triangle.=E2=80=
=9D  This means we are to solve for all missing side lengths and angle meas=
urements.<br>
</p><div id=3D"attachment_16396" style=3D"width: 1290px" class=3D"wp-captio=
n aligncenter"><img aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-16396" src=3D"ht=
tps://calcworkshop.com/wp-content/uploads/right-triangle-trig-missing-sides=
-angles.png" alt=3D"right triangle trig finding missing sides and angles" w=
idth=3D"1280" height=3D"720" data-pin-nopin=3D"true" class=3D"size-full wp-=
image-16396"><p id=3D"caption-attachment-16396" class=3D"wp-caption-text">F=
inding Sides and Angles Using Inverse Trig</p></div> <p></p>
<h2>Common Questions</h2>
<p><b>Q</b>: Is sohcahtoa only for right triangles?<br>
<b>A</b>: Yes, it only applies to right triangles.  If we have an oblique t=
riangle, then we can=E2=80=99t assume these trig ratios will work.  We have=
 other methods we=E2=80=99ll learn about in Math Analysis and Trigonometry =
such as the laws of sines and cosines to handle those cases.</p>
<p><b>Q</b>: When to use sohcahtoa?<br>
<b>A</b>: When you are given a right triangle, where two of the side length=
s are given and you are asked to find the third side.</p>
<p><b>Q</b>: Where is the hypotenuse of a right triangle?<br>
<b>A</b>: They hypotenuse of a right triangle is always opposite the 90 deg=
ree angle, and is the longest side.</p>
<p><b>Q</b>: Where is the adjacent side of a triangle?<br>
<b>A</b>: The adjacent side of a triangle is the side (leg) that is touchin=
g the angle but is not the hypotenuse.  </p>
<p><b>Q</b>: What does it mean to solve a right triangle?<br>
<b>A</b>: When you solve a right triangle, or any triangle for that matter,=
 it means you need to find all missing sides and angles.  Therefore,  you w=
ill use Trig Ratios, the Triangle Sum Theorem, and/or the Pythagorean Theor=
em to find any missing angle or side length measures.</p>
<p>In the video below, you=E2=80=99ll progress through harder examples invo=
lving trig ratios, calculating missing side lengths and angles, inverse tri=
g, and much more!</p>
